<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=10025500793991></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f10025500793991><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=43308&mid=10025500793991>Interesting Tricks</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=43308&mid=10025500793991#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=108438><span id= >Aeldwan</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>1 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Oct 8th 10:07 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I know not everyone who is an Enchanter uses the Color Flux/Shift/Slant line of Point Blank AE stun. Mostly because they are afraid to get into the fight, especially after dropping huge debuffs onto your helpless victims. But not only can these spells give you 4/6/8 seconds of needed escape/mez time, but also you can keep a group stunned nearly forever while anyone else in the group beats them to death, casts on them, or whatever you wish. Not to mention your AE Mez after the fun is over. Now. The trick I love the most, is to have a wizard of 29th+ AE Snare a few blue things and kite them through you. Now you may think.. gah! I'm dead! BUT, they want your earstwhile friend far more.. Simply use your 4 second stun, then your 6 second stun, and then back out of the mess while your Wizard/Mage friend Rains death on them. 2 Rain spells do incredible damage and are rarely resisted if you rain Alternating elements. With 10 Seconds to play with your small group of 2 can kite a horde of up to 8 snared creatures as this is generally the most the stun, the snare, and the rain can affect. Once you have backed away from your little group, cast your AE Mez in timing with the last wave of the other caster's rain, and catch most all of the battered and bruised monsters in one swoop. Again they cannot cast, and just sit there. You Root or DD any of the escapees, and both of you med. After 12 seconds, he stands up and throws his AE DD and you Mez what's left(In my experience if they're blue, NOT MUCH) and DD any stragglers. This is the easiest to do after 24th as you get a decent DD then, and should have all your important research spells such as Color Shift and Mesmerization. A Druid can do much the same at that level, but has to snare kite them into a cluster and run them through you. He uses Pogonip for the AE Rain, and any AE DD available. Even Clerics can do this with their Word line of AE PB DD spells but there has to be someone snaring. I recommend more than one Cleric for this.. the cycle time on the spell is slow, and it is not mana efficient. At 39th level you can join the fun with Gravity Flux. At 44th the Color Slant spell comes available, and will allow you to cast your Flux into them after Slant, and STILL get your Mez off at the end. 18 seconds is forever when your a mob taking 250+ damage almost every second for 18 seconds along with 3 or 8 of your friends. This has worked beautifully now in Lake of Ill Omen, Overthere, Ice Clad, and Stonebrunt. Many other zones are not conducive to kiting, or don't have camps your wizard can pull with a single AE snare. An extra Wizard, Druid, Mage, Cleric or other AE DD/snare using class are always welcome. Safer for all.<br><br>Aeldwan the Tactician<br>Wanderers of the Realm<br>Morrel-Thule<br>"It worked! Um.. well.. of course it did! Let's see if we can do it again!"<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
